Commissioner Bud Selig and Major League Baseball have taken a lot of heat over the last several months for their supposed failure to grapple forthrightly with the sport's steroid problem. Before the mid-1990s, the substances of choice in the clubhouse were amphetamines and recreational drugs. They would benefit from taking a step back and looking more carefully at the evolution of the steroid problem in baseball. Indeed, it was probably around 10 years ago that some people in baseball became aware that anabolic steroids were being used by some players. 